          "body": "The gleaning image of verse 9 is devastating in its agricultural precision. Grapes are harvested once; then the workers go back through the vineyard a second time picking the clusters left behind. God commands the same treatment for Israel's remnant: even what survives the first wave of judgment will be stripped by a second pass. Verse 10 marks the prophet's anguish at his own mission: 'To whom shall I speak and give warning that they may hear?' The ears are *arel* — uncircumcised, closed, impervious. The word of the LORD has become not merely irrelevant but a *reproach* to them, an object of active contempt. Verse 11 is among the most psychologically intense moments in all of Jeremiah: he is 'full of the wrath of the LORD,' weary of holding it in. The prophet's interior life has been colonized by the divine anger he is commissioned to announce. God then speaks through him the scope of the judgment: children, young men, husbands, wives, the aged, the very old — no demographic is exempt. Houses, fields, and wives will pass to others (6:12). The judgment is total."
