          "body": "The chapter closes with a remarkable commissioning of Jeremiah: God appoints him as an *bachon* (assayer, tester) and a *mivtsar* (examiner of fortified ore), to test the quality of the people as a metallurgist tests metal. The image of the forge and the furnace was a standard ancient metaphor for divine judgment (Isaiah 1:25; Ezekiel 22:17-22; Malachi 3:2-3). In those texts, the refining is restorative — God purifies what can be purified. In Jeremiah 6, the refining fails completely. The bellows blow fiercely, the lead is consumed, the fire burns maximally — but the wicked are not separated from the silver (6:29). The refining yields nothing. The concluding verdict in verse 30 — 'rejected silver, because the LORD has rejected them' — is a wordplay in the Hebrew: *maas* (reject) appears twice, the second as divine passive. The people are called rejected silver because the LORD has rejected them. Their rejection of His law (6:19) is answered by His rejection of them (6:30). The chapter that began with an alarm calling people to flee the coming destruction ends with God's final verdict that the destruction is deserved and the people beyond refinement. It is the bleakest closing verse in the first major cycle of Jeremiah's preaching."
